# Kolibri: Small Form Factor PC

---

## Background

I have built my own PCs since I was a teenager, starting with a Pentium 166Mhz in the 90s, and it has always been fun, exciting and educational. Building doesn't necessarily save any money compared to buying a pre-built machine, but you always end up learning something new, and it leaves you with a sense of pride, achievement and a deeper connection to your little digital helper.

This particular build has evolved from a standard Cooler Master Elite 130 Mini-ITX case with a small water cooling loop for the CPU. Mini ITX is my preferred form factor, ever since I have lived with limited space in a caravan and a tiny house on wheels.

The PC in the original case worked well for a long time, but I was never quite happy with some of its short-comings. And when the already noisy water pump started developing a nasty grinding sound, it was time for some modifications. Enter the Kolibri! üê§

Kolibri translates to Hummingbird, since I wanted the PC to be small, quiet and air-cooled (think flip-flapping wings üòù)

The original case looked like [this](https://www.coolermaster.com/catalog/cases/mini-itx/elite130/). Not terrible, but not the best for proper desktop sized air cooling.

### Goals

- I wanted to create a 'Wind Tunnel' air flow layout. Air in from the front and out the back, with large fans in serial, blowing along that axis.
- I wanted to get rid of the ATX PSU on top of the CPU to make room for a 120mm CPU cooler. Instead of the PSU, I wanted another large exhaust fan on the back of the case.

### Modifications

The first step was to get a small, high quality SFX format power supply and remove the massive ATX PSU. The only spot I could move the new supply to was in the middle of the case, under the drive bay. I cut into the bottom of the case to create a new mount with air outlet for it. The PSU needs to be plugged in from the bottom now, which is a bit different and requires an angle piece for the IEC plug. No biggie though! üòÖ

There was plenty of room above the motherboard now , which fits the wonderfully quiet, efficient and massive Noctua NH-U12S 120mm CPU cooler perfectly.

The new exhaust opening was cut and drilled into the back of the case. All of these cuts were unfortunately made with a jigsaw with pretty blunt blades üòÜ, since that was the only tool I had available that day, which led to some embarrassingly wonky cuts. A bit of black spray paint hid that hideous handy work sufficiently and a grill was mounted to the back to keep fingers from fan blades.

